        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-6715.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from John Murray, 28 April [1869]</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">The <hi rend="italic">Quarterly Review</hi> was published by John Murray; he had evidently sent the issue containing an anonymous review by <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4935.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Alfred Russel Wallace</ref> that discussed CD’s theory of natural selection ([Wallace] 1869b; see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-6715.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from John Murray, 28 April [1869]</ref>). CD also refers to the bishop of Oxford, <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_5128.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Samuel Wilberforce</ref>, and <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3629.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Richard Owen</ref>, both notable opponents of CD’s theory. The ‘Ladies’ would have been <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1218.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Emma Darwin</ref>, Henrietta Darwin, and Elizabeth Darwin; it is not known why they burned the cover.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3026.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">John Lubbock</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-6715.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from John Murray, 28 April [1869]</ref> and n. 2.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">CD refers to <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6018.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Origin</hi> 5th ed.</ref> and to <hi rend="italic">Descent.</hi></note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f6">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-6706.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to A. R. Wallace, 14 April 1869</ref> and n. 12.</note>
